Livy'has put a clever speech in the mouth ol Alorcus. He begins by stating his errand and placing the responsibility for it on Alco, their fellow-citizen (civis, emphatic), who has failed to complete what he undertook, as he has not brought the terms oi peace from Hannibal which he went for. Alorcus declares that , he has therefore come out of interest in them, being their guest friend. He did not suggest peace as long as he saw that there was hope of their success. With such an introduction as this Alorcus may now state the terme and urge an acceptance of them on the ground of necessity. His last sentence pictores the disaster which non-compliance with these terms implies.
